Upon neutralisation, $[\mathrm{NaCl}]=0.05 \mathrm{M}$
$\therefore \wedge_m=\frac{0.0056}{0.05} \times 1000=112 \mathrm{~S} \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$

On further addition of equal volume of acid, the solution is $\frac{0.1}{3} \mathrm{M}$ in NaCl and $\frac{0.1}{3} \mathrm{M}$ in HCl
$\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{K}_{\text {solution }}=\mathrm{K}_{\mathrm{NaCl}}+\mathrm{K}_{\mathrm{HCl}} \\
& =\left(\frac{0.1}{3} \times 112+\frac{0.1}{3} \times 400\right) \times 10^{-3} \\
& =0.017 \mathrm{~S} \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}
\end{aligned}$

The Molar conductivity of the dissociated form of $\mathrm{H}_6 \mathrm{C}_4 \mathrm{O}_2$ is
$\begin{aligned}
& \wedge_m^{\circ}\left(\mathrm{H}^{+}, \mathrm{H}_5 \mathrm{C}_4 \mathrm{O}_2^{-}\right)=\wedge_{\mathrm{m}}^{\circ}(\mathrm{HCl})+\wedge_{\mathrm{m}}^{\circ} \mathrm{NaH}_5 \mathrm{C}_4 \mathrm{O}_2-\wedge_{\mathrm{m}}^{\circ}(\mathrm{NaCl}) \\
& =426+83-126=383 \mathrm{~S} \mathrm{~cm}^2 \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}$
The molar conductivity of $\mathrm{H}_6 \mathrm{C}_4 \mathrm{O}_2=$
$\begin{aligned}
& \frac{3.83 \times 10^{-5} \times 1000}{0.001} \\
& =38.3 \mathrm{~S} \mathrm{~cm}^2 \mathrm{~mol}^{-1} \\
& \alpha=\frac{38.3}{383}=0.1 \\
& \mathrm{~K}_{\mathrm{a}}=\frac{\mathrm{C}^2}{1-\alpha}=1.11 \times 10^{-5}
\end{aligned}$

